vectorData.altText: 16. Ventricular systole causes the semilunar valves to ___________ (open/close).
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
That's right!  Ventricular systole causes the semilunar valves to open. This allows blood to enter into the pulmonary or systemic circulation.

A valve, by definition, permits one-way flow. 
The contraction of ventricular myocardium during ventricular systole increases pressure in these chambers. Because of the distinct structure of the valves, this increased pressure forces the semilunar valves open and the atrioventricular valves closed. 
This ensures the one-way flow of blood during ventricular systole through the opened semilunar valves and into their efferent vessels, the pulmonary trunk and the ascending aorta. Meanwhile, because the atrioventricular valves are forced shut during ventricular systole, the backflow of blood into the atria is prevented.
